\details{
The \code{tests} argument is a character vector. Each element has one of the forms
\code{TEST}, \code{TEST_UG}, \code{TEST_ML}, \code{TEST_RLS}, \code{TEST_UG_ML}, or \code{TEST_UG_RLS}.
For example, \code{SB_UG_RLS}.
\itemize{
\item The first part names the test. The available names are listed below.
\item Add \code{UG} to use the unbiased estimator of the fourth-order moment matrix
from Du and Bentler (2022). Leave it out to use the standard biased matrix.
Performance depends on the data-generating process, so neither gamma choice
dominates in every setting.
\item The final part chooses the chi-square statistic. \code{ML} uses the
normal-discrepancy statistic (Bollen, 1989). \code{RLS} uses Browne's (1974)
reweighted least squares statistic.
}

The \code{peba} method is the recommended default. It partitions the eigenvalues
into \code{j} equally sized sets (if not possible, the smallest set is incomplete),
shrinks them towards their common mean, and averages within each set. Provide
a positive integer \code{j} no greater than the test df. Values from \code{2} through
\code{6} are usually good candidates. The method was introduced by Foldnes, Moss,
and Grønneberg
(2025).

\code{pols} is a penalized regression method with a finite positive penalization
term. Foldnes, Moss, and Grønneberg (2025) studied \code{pols=2}, which has
good performance in a variety of contexts.

\code{pall} penalizes all eigenvalues in ugamma, while \code{all} uses all eigenvalues
without penalization. \code{pall} is the recommended option for nested models, for
which the penalized methods were extended and evaluated by Foldnes,
Grønneberg, and Moss (2026).

The \code{eba} method is the unpenalized predecessor of \code{peba} (Foldnes and
Grønneberg, 2018). It averages within the eigenvalue blocks without
shrinkage. \code{peba} usually performs better. \code{eba} remains available for
comparisons, and values from \code{j=2} through \code{j=4} tend to work best.

Familiar corrections are available too:
\itemize{
\item \code{std} uses the ordinary chi-square reference distribution.
\item \code{sb} gives the Satorra--Bentler \emph{p}-value (Satorra and Bentler, 1994).
\item \code{ss} gives the scaled and shifted \emph{p}-value (Asparouhov and Muthén, 2010).
\item \code{sf} gives the scaled \emph{F} \emph{p}-value (Wu and Lin, 2016).
}
\subsection{Estimators and data types}{

\link{semTests-support} (\code{?semTests-support}) gives the complete matrix of
supported estimators, data types, and configurations. Here is the short
version.

The limiting null law of the test statistic is a weighted sum of
chi-squares for any minimum-discrepancy estimator. \code{pvalues()} supports
ML/MLM/MLR, GLS, ULS,
FIML (missing data), and categorical DWLS/ULS families, with single- and
multi-group continuous, ordered, and mixed-indicator fits.
\code{pvalues_nested()} supports continuous estimators and categorical
Satorra-2000 comparisons with a delta restriction map. The fitted model must
expose the asymptotic moment covariance. Robust choices such as
\code{test = "satorra.bentler"} or \code{estimator = "MLM"}, \code{"MLR"}, or \code{"DWLS"}
provide it. The RLS statistic (\code{browne.residual.nt.model}) and the unbiased
(\code{UG}) Du-Bentler gamma are defined for the classical continuous,
complete-data ML case. Other families use the standard statistic and biased
gamma. Full WLS/ADF is refused outright: its weight is already the inverse
moment covariance, so the correction is exactly the identity and every test
would equal the ordinary chi-square.

GLS, ULS, categorical DWLS/ULS, FIML missing data, and nested FIML or
categorical comparison are validated to numerical tolerance against an
independent implementation and are marked stable; see the Stability section
in \link{semTests-support}.

Both entry points require a converged fit and warn if lavaan reports an
inadmissible solution. Nested comparisons require the same requested
estimator, fitting conventions, variables, groups, sample sizes, raw data,
and missingness mask. \code{semTests} checks comparability. The substantive
nesting argument remains part of the analysis.

For FIML, \code{fiml.convention = "observed"} (the default) uses observed
saturated and model information throughout. An independent implementation
validates this construction. The \code{"lavaan"} option reproduces lavaan
0.7-2's robust-test construction. For a single model it uses lavaan's
inspected \code{UGamma}. For nested models it uses lavaan's H1 weight convention
and selected model information. The returned object records the convention,
which keeps this inferential choice visible in saved results.

For a single FIML model, \code{"lavaan"} means the eigenvalue spectrum returned by
\code{lavInspect(fit, "UGamma")}. The scalar Yuan--Bentler--Mplus test stored by a
default MLR fit is a different correction and may give a different result.
For nested FIML models, \code{"lavaan"} reproduces
\code{lavTestLRT(..., method = "satorra.2000")}.
}
